  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "gKJr2NrXhKnWhDZMXl2yRIQ5XdM=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:26.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Vulnerability (fixed)\n\nThe original document-sharing code derived its encryption key as:\n\n```\nkey = SHA-256(sender_address + \":\" + recipient_address)\n```\n\nBoth inputs are public (on-chain, ENS, etherscan). Any third party who knew both addresses could reconstruct the key and decrypt any shared bundle. This was **security theater**, not encryption.\n\n## Fix: Swarm ACT (Access Control Trie)\n\nACT derives its session key via ECDH:\n\n```\nsession_key = SHA-256( ECDH(publisher_privkey, grantee_pubkey) || salt )\n```\n\nThe publisher's **private key** is required \u2014 only their Bee node has it. A third party with both public keys still faces the discrete-log problem.\n\n## Comparison\n\n| | Old (deriveShareKey) | New (ACT) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Key derivation | `SHA-256(public_addr_a + public_addr_b)` | `ECDH(privkey \u00d7 pubkey) + salt` |\n| Third-party attack | Trivial | Impossible \u2014 DLP |\n| Encryption | App-level AES-256-GCM | Bee node native |\n| Grantee management | None | `patchGrantees()` add/remove |\n| Revocation | Impossible | Rebuild ACT with new access key |\n\n## Status\n\nShareManager rewritten, 105/105 tests passing. ACT now protects document sharing, chat history feeds, and multi-party collaboration data.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:26.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:26.000Z"
    }
  },
